/* PasstheEPPP — Question Bank Batch 50
   90 new questions — I-O Psychology, Development, Social-Cultural, Research/Stats */
(function(){
    if (typeof EPPPData === 'undefined') return;

    const batch50 = [
        // === I-O Psychology (20) ===
        {domainId:3, q:"Transformational leadership (Bass & Avolio) is characterized by:", options:["Only offering contingent rewards and punishment based on measurable task performance outcomes","Four I's: Idealized Influence, Inspirational Motivation, Intellectual Stimulation, and Individualized Consideration","Adopting a completely hands-off laissez-faire management approach to subordinate task completion","Only monitoring for deviations and punishing poor performance through management by exception"], answer:1, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Correct: (B) Transformational leadership: leaders inspire followers to transcend self-interest for the group. Idealized influence (role modeling), inspirational motivation (compelling vision), intellectual stimulation (challenging assumptions), individualized consideration (mentoring each person).\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) Contingent rewards characterize transactional leadership style.\n(C) Laissez-faire is a separate and generally ineffective leadership style.\n(D) Management by exception is a component of transactional leadership."},
        {domainId:3, q:"Holland's RIASEC model proposes:", options:["Six personality types matching occupational environments: Realistic, Investigative, Artistic, Social, Enterprising, Conventional","Only two broadly defined career personality types requiring vocational classification assessment","That occupational career choice is fundamentally random and unrelated to personal characteristics","That individual personality traits have no meaningful influence on vocational career preferences"], answer:0, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Correct: (A) Holland: person-environment fit in career choice. Six types form a hexagon; adjacent types are more similar. Congruence between personality type and work environment predicts satisfaction and stability. Measured by the Self-Directed Search (SDS).\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(B) Six distinct personality types are proposed, not two.\n(C) Career choice relates systematically to personality-environment fit.\n(D) Personality is absolutely central to Holland's occupational theory."},
        {domainId:3, q:"Organizational Citizenship Behavior (OCB) refers to:", options:["Only mandatory job duties formally specified within official position description documents","Voluntary employee behaviors going beyond formal job requirements that benefit the organization","Counterproductive workplace deviance behaviors that undermine organizational effectiveness systematically","Chronic employee absenteeism patterns resulting from low organizational commitment and disengagement"], answer:1, difficulty:"easy", rationale:"Correct: (B) OCBs: discretionary behaviors not directly rewarded by the formal system. Includes altruism (helping coworkers), conscientiousness (going beyond minimums), sportsmanship, courtesy, civic virtue. OCBs predict organizational effectiveness. First described by Organ (1988).\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) OCBs are specifically BEYOND formal required job duties.\n(C) Deviance is counterproductive behavior, the direct opposite of OCB.\n(D) Absenteeism is a separate organizational behavior construct."},
        {domainId:3, q:"Vroom's Expectancy Theory of motivation proposes that motivation equals:", options:["Only the absolute salary level offered regardless of individual perceptions or comparisons","Expectancy (E→P) × Instrumentality (P→O) × Valence — effort leads to valued performance outcomes","Only overall job satisfaction derived from intrinsic motivational factors and hygiene variables","Only the fear of organizational punishment for substandard performance and policy violations"], answer:1, difficulty:"hard", rationale:"Correct: (B) Vroom: M = E × I × V. Expectancy: belief that effort → performance. Instrumentality: belief that performance → outcomes. Valence: value placed on the outcomes. If any factor is zero, motivation is zero. Cognitive choice theory.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) Salary is just one potential outcome affecting valence.\n(C) Satisfaction is an outcome, not part of the motivational calculation.\n(D) Punishment is one outcome type, but motivation involves the full multiplicative model."},
        {domainId:3, q:"Structured interviews are superior to unstructured interviews because:", options:["They are substantially shorter in overall administration duration compared to unstructured formats","They have higher inter-rater reliability, criterion validity, and reduced bias from standardized questions","They are more enjoyable and entertaining for both the interviewer and the job candidates","They require virtually no advance preparation, job analysis, or rating scale development work"], answer:1, difficulty:"easy", rationale:"Correct: (B) Structured interviews: standardized questions, behavioral/situational focus, anchored rating scales. Meta-analyses show validity of .51 vs. .38 for unstructured. Reduce interviewer bias, first impressions, and non-job-relevant factors.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) The superiority is about validity and reliability, not duration.\n(C) Entertainment value is not the relevant psychometric criterion.\n(D) Structured interviews require significant preparation including job analysis and rating scales."},
        {domainId:3, q:"Adverse impact (disparate impact) in employee selection is typically identified using:", options:["Only informal employee complaints submitted through organizational grievance reporting channels","The four-fifths (80%) rule — if a minority group's rate is less than 80% of majority rate","Only formal discrimination lawsuits filed through the Equal Employment Opportunity Commission","Only subjective hiring manager opinions about the representativeness of applicant pools"], answer:1, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Correct: (B) Four-fifths rule: if the selection rate for a protected group is less than 80% of the rate for the highest-scoring group, adverse impact may exist. Example: if 50% of White applicants are hired, at least 40% (0.80 × 50%) of minority applicants should be hired.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) The rule provides an objective statistical threshold, not informal complaints.\n(C) Legal action isn't required to identify potential adverse impact.\n(D) Objective statistical criteria, not subjective opinion, drive the analysis."},
        {domainId:3, q:"Job Demands-Resources (JD-R) theory proposes:", options:["Only job demands matter for predicting employee burnout and organizational health outcomes","Job demands predict burnout (health impairment), while job resources predict engagement (motivation)","Only organizational resources matter for predicting employee engagement and performance outcomes","That workplace characteristics have no measurable empirical impact on employee health outcomes"], answer:1, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Correct: (B) JD-R (Bakker & Demerouti): two parallel processes. High demands (workload, emotional demands) → burnout → health problems. High resources (autonomy, feedback, support) → engagement → positive outcomes. Resources buffer the demand-burnout link.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) Both demands and resources matter through dual parallel pathways.\n(C) Both dimensions are important predictors within the theoretical model.\n(D) Extensive empirical evidence links work characteristics to employee health."},
        {domainId:3, q:"360-degree feedback involves:", options:["Only supervisor ratings collected during annual formal performance appraisal review meetings","Performance evaluation data from multiple sources: supervisor, peers, subordinates, self, and customers","Only self-evaluation ratings compared against objective organizational performance benchmarks","Only peer ratings collected anonymously through standardized organizational survey instruments"], answer:1, difficulty:"easy", rationale:"Correct: (B) 360-degree: multi-source feedback providing a comprehensive view of performance. Reduces single-source bias. Most useful for development rather than administrative decisions. Self-other rating discrepancies can identify blind spots.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A)(C)(D) By definition, 360-degree feedback includes multiple diverse sources."},
        {domainId:3, q:"Hackman and Oldham's Job Characteristics Model identifies five core job dimensions:", options:["Only compensation salary and fringe benefits offered within the employment compensation package","Skill variety, task identity, task significance, autonomy, and feedback affecting psychological states","Only total weekly work hours and scheduling flexibility within the employment arrangement","Only social relationships and interpersonal dynamics with coworkers in the work environment"], answer:1, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Correct: (B) Five core dimensions → three psychological states: experienced meaningfulness (from skill variety, task identity, task significance), experienced responsibility (from autonomy), knowledge of results (from feedback) → outcomes: satisfaction, motivation, low turnover.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) The model focuses on intrinsic job characteristics, not compensation.\n(C) Work hours aren't a core dimension in this model.\n(D) Social relationships aren't included as core dimensions (though important)."},
        {domainId:3, q:"Procedural justice in organizations refers to:", options:["Only pay fairness and equitable compensation distribution across similar organizational positions","The perceived fairness of the PROCESSES used to make decisions (consistency, bias correction, voice)","Only outcome fairness reflected in the proportional distribution of organizational rewards received","Only interpersonal treatment quality experienced during supervisory interactions with employees"], answer:1, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Correct: (B) Procedural justice (Thibaut & Walker; Leventhal): fairness of decision-making procedures. Leventhal's criteria: consistency, bias suppression, accuracy, correctability, representativeness, ethicality. Distinct from distributive justice (outcome fairness) and interactional justice.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) Pay fairness relates specifically to distributive justice.\n(C) Outcome fairness defines distributive justice, not procedural.\n(D) Interpersonal treatment quality defines interactional justice."},
        {domainId:3, q:"Assessment centers are used in selection because:", options:["They are the cheapest and most cost-effective personnel selection methodology currently available","They use multiple methods (simulations, in-basket, role plays) to assess multiple competencies validly","They only require approximately five minutes of total candidate assessment administration time","They rely on only one single standardized psychometric test instrument for candidate evaluation"], answer:1, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Correct: (B) Assessment centers: multiple assessors evaluate multiple candidates on multiple dimensions using multiple exercises (work simulations). Content validity is high due to job relevance. Used for management selection and development. Expensive but valid.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) Assessment centers are among the most expensive selection methods.\n(C) They typically require 1-3 full days of assessment activities.\n(D) Multiple exercises and methods are the defining characteristic feature."},
        {domainId:3, q:"The Peter Principle states:", options:["That every organizational employee is perpetually competent at each successive hierarchical level","Employees tend to be promoted to their level of incompetence — rising until beyond their abilities","That all organizational promotion decisions are inherently fair and merit-based without systemic bias","That only the most objectively qualified candidates ever receive organizational advancement opportunities"], answer:1, difficulty:"easy", rationale:"Correct: (B) Peter Principle (Laurence Peter, 1969): in hierarchical organizations, employees are promoted based on current competence, but the promoted position requires different skills. They rise until they reach a level where they're no longer competent and remain there.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) The principle suggests eventual incompetence at higher organizational levels.\n(C) The principle highlights a systemic flaw in hierarchical promotion systems.\n(D) The principle suggests good performers get promoted until they can't perform."},
        {domainId:3, q:"Psychological capital (PsyCap, Luthans) includes:", options:["Only financial monetary capital resources available for organizational investment and operations","Self-efficacy, hope, resilience, and optimism — positive psychological states predicting performance","Only general cognitive intelligence as measured by standardized psychometric IQ assessment tools","Only physical health and cardiovascular fitness levels of organizational workforce members"], answer:1, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Correct: (B) PsyCap: four positive psychological resources that are state-like (developable). Self-efficacy (confidence), hope (goal-directed energy + pathways), resilience (bouncing back), optimism (positive attribution). Meta-analyses show PsyCap predicts performance, satisfaction, well-being.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) PsyCap is psychological capital, categorically distinct from financial capital.\n(C) Intelligence is relatively stable; PsyCap resources are specifically developable.\n(D) Physical health is distinct from the four psychological capital components."},
        {domainId:3, q:"Goal-Setting Theory (Locke & Latham) finds that the most effective goals are:", options:["Vague and easy, allowing maximum flexibility and minimal performance pressure on employees","Specific and challenging (but achievable) with feedback and commitment from goal participants","Deliberately impossible to achieve, designed to maximize aspirational striving beyond capacity","Set exclusively by others without any participative input from the individuals performing tasks"], answer:1, difficulty:"easy", rationale:"Correct: (B) Specific, difficult goals lead to higher performance than 'do your best' or easy goals. Moderators: commitment, feedback, task complexity, self-efficacy. Goals direct attention, regulate effort, increase persistence, and motivate strategy development.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) Vague, easy goals consistently produce lower performance in research studies.\n(C) Impossible goals decrease motivation and create learned helplessness.\n(D) Participative goal-setting increases commitment and subsequent performance."},
        {domainId:3, q:"Organizational culture differs from organizational climate in that:", options:["They are completely identical constructs measuring exactly the same organizational phenomenon","Culture refers to deep shared values and assumptions; climate refers to surface perceptions of practices","Only organizational culture matters for understanding employee behavior and performance outcomes","Only organizational climate matters for predicting organizational effectiveness and employee outcomes"], answer:1, difficulty:"hard", rationale:"Correct: (B) Culture: deeply held, often unspoken assumptions and values (qualitative, anthropological roots). Climate: employees' shared perceptions of what the organization rewards, supports, and expects (quantitative, psychological roots). Culture is 'what we believe'; climate is 'what we experience.'\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) They are related but conceptually distinct organizational constructs.\n(C)(D) Both culture and climate are important for understanding organizations."},
        {domainId:3, q:"Situational Leadership Theory (Hersey & Blanchard) proposes that leadership style should vary based on:", options:["Only the leader's fixed personality traits and dispositional characteristics across all situations","The follower's readiness or developmental level for a specific task — from directing to delegating","Only the organization's total employee headcount size and number of hierarchical reporting levels","Only the specific industry type and external market conditions facing the organization currently"], answer:1, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Correct: (B) Situational Leadership: effective leaders match their style to follower readiness. Four styles: Telling/Directing (high task, low relationship), Selling/Coaching, Participating/Supporting, Delegating. As follower competence and commitment increase, the leader moves from directive to delegating.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) The theory specifically focuses on follower readiness, not leader traits.\n(C)(D) The theory is about leader-follower dynamics, not organizational characteristics."},
        {domainId:3, q:"Realistic Job Previews (RJPs) are effective because:", options:["They systematically make all job positions sound substantially better than actual working conditions","They provide honest positive AND negative job information, reducing turnover through accurate expectations","They completely eliminate all employee voluntary turnover from the hiring organization permanently","They fully replace all other selection interview methods throughout the entire hiring assessment process"], answer:1, difficulty:"easy", rationale:"Correct: (B) RJPs: candidates receive balanced information (not just positive marketing). Research shows RJPs reduce turnover (self-selection out), increase job satisfaction and commitment, and improve person-organization fit. The vaccination effect: inoculates against future disillusionment.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) RJPs deliberately include negative aspects alongside positive ones.\n(C) They reduce but cannot completely eliminate voluntary turnover.\n(D) RJPs supplement the selection process rather than replacing other methods."},
        {domainId:3, q:"Work-family conflict research shows that:", options:["It only affects women who are simultaneously managing professional careers and childcare duties","Conflict is bidirectional — work interferes with family AND family interferes with work distinctly","It has absolutely no meaningful organizational consequences on productivity or employee retention","It only affects parents with young children and not other categories of organizational employees"], answer:1, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Correct: (B) Work-family conflict is bidirectional: WIF (work → family) predicted by work hours, demands, inflexibility; FIW (family → work) predicted by family stressors. Both predict reduced health, satisfaction, and performance. Affects all employees, not just parents or women.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) Work-family conflict affects all genders equally in research studies.\n(C) It has significant organizational consequences including increased turnover and absenteeism.\n(D) Non-parents also experience work-life demands and role conflict."},
        {domainId:3, q:"Content validity evidence is established by:", options:["Correlating test scores with concurrent or predictive job performance criterion measurements","Systematic analysis showing test content adequately samples the knowledge and skills required by the job","Conducting confirmatory factor analysis to evaluate the underlying latent construct measurement model","Evaluating test length alone as the sole determinant of adequate domain content coverage"], answer:1, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Correct: (B) Content validity: domain experts evaluate whether test items adequately represent the construct or job domain. Based on job analysis → test blueprint → item review. No correlation coefficient; it's a judgmental rather than statistical evaluation. Important for achievement and certification tests.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) Correlation with performance establishes criterion-related validity.\n(C) Factor analysis provides construct validity evidence, not content.\n(D) Test length alone doesn't establish adequate content domain coverage."},
        {domainId:3, q:"Equity theory (Adams) predicts that employees who feel OVERPAID will:", options:["Simply do nothing because favorable inequity creates no psychological tension or discomfort","Experience inequity tension and may increase work quality/quantity or cognitively distort comparisons","Simply enjoy the extra money without any psychological tension or behavioral adjustment needed","Immediately quit the organization as their first and most probable behavioral response option"], answer:1, difficulty:"hard", rationale:"Correct: (B) Overpayment inequity: the person's outcome/input ratio exceeds the referent's. To restore equity: increase inputs (work harder/more), decrease outcomes (rare), distort perceptions, change referent, or leave. Research: overpaid hourly workers increase quality; piece-rate workers increase quantity.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) Equity theory predicts psychological tension and behavioral responses even from favorable inequity.\n(C) Inequity (even favorable) creates measurable psychological tension.\n(D) Quitting is one option but not the typical first behavioral response."},

        // === Social-Cultural (15) ===
        {domainId:4, q:"Stereotype threat (Steele & Aronson) occurs when:", options:["Negative group stereotypes are invariably accurate reflections of actual performance differences","Awareness of a negative group stereotype creates anxiety that can impair performance on tasks","Stereotypes have absolutely no measurable effect on any aspect of cognitive task performance","Only racial and ethnic minority groups ever experience stereotype-related performance decrements"], answer:1, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Correct: (B) Stereotype threat: knowing a negative stereotype applies to your group → anxiety → reduced working memory → impaired performance. Classic finding: Black students performed worse on 'diagnostic' tests when race was salient. Whites showed threat on athletic tasks. Women on math.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) Stereotype threat concerns the psychological effects, not accuracy, of stereotypes.\n(C) Research consistently shows significant measurable performance effects.\n(D) Any group with a relevant negative stereotype can experience the threat."},
        {domainId:4, q:"Social Identity Theory (Tajfel & Turner) proposes that:", options:["People fundamentally have no meaningful psychological group affiliations or social identifications","People derive self-esteem from group memberships and favor in-groups over out-groups systematically","All intergroup relations are inherently harmonious and cooperative without competitive tension","Only individual personal identity contributes to self-concept, not social group membership identity"], answer:1, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Correct: (B) Social Identity Theory: self-concept includes personal identity AND social identity (derived from group memberships). In-group favoritism and out-group discrimination arise from the motivation to maintain positive social identity. Minimal group paradigm: even arbitrary grouping creates favoritism.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) Group affiliations are absolutely central to the entire theory.\n(C) Intergroup conflict and competition are key phenomena the theory explains.\n(D) Both personal and social identity contribute to overall self-concept."},
        {domainId:4, q:"The bystander effect (Darley & Latané) refers to:", options:["People always immediately help in every emergency situation regardless of surrounding circumstances","Decreased likelihood of helping as the number of bystanders increases, from diffusion of responsibility","Bystanders invariably intervene in emergencies with greater frequency when more witnesses are present","The phenomenon occurring only in densely populated urban geographical areas and never suburban settings"], answer:1, difficulty:"easy", rationale:"Correct: (B) Bystander effect: more witnesses → less individual helping. Mechanisms: diffusion of responsibility ('someone else will help'), pluralistic ignorance (looking at others' inaction and concluding no emergency), evaluation apprehension (fear of embarrassment). Kitty Genovese case sparked research.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) The effect demonstrates specifically reduced helping with more bystanders.\n(C) The opposite is demonstrated — more bystanders leads to less individual intervention.\n(D) The effect has been replicated across diverse settings and geographical contexts."},
        {domainId:4, q:"Obedience research by Milgram found that:", options:["Virtually nobody obeys destructive authority commands under any experimental research conditions","Approximately 65% of participants administered maximum 'shock' when instructed by an authority figure","Only clinically diagnosable psychopaths demonstrate obedience to destructive authority figure commands","Destructive obedience to authority occurs exclusively within formal military organizational chain-of-command structures"], answer:1, difficulty:"easy", rationale:"Correct: (B) Milgram's obedience studies: ~65% of participants went to the maximum 450-volt level. Factors increasing obedience: proximity to authority, distance from victim, institutional setting, incremental escalation, no model of disobedience. Demonstrated the power of situational forces.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) The surprising finding was the remarkably HIGH rate of obedience.\n(C) Normal, psychologically well-adjusted people demonstrated obedience.\n(D) Obedience to authority occurs across many diverse organizational contexts."},
        {domainId:4, q:"Cognitive dissonance theory (Festinger) predicts that insufficient justification leads to:", options:["No measurable attitude change regardless of the magnitude of justification provided externally","Greater attitude change — small external justification drives internal attribution and belief shifts","Complete psychological apathy and total disengagement from the counter-attitudinal behavior performed","Only observable behavioral change without any corresponding shift in underlying cognitive attitude"], answer:1, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Correct: (B) Insufficient justification: when people perform a counter-attitudinal behavior for a small reward (insufficient external justification), they experience dissonance and change their attitude to match the behavior. Classic: $1 condition → more attitude change than $20 condition.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) Dissonance theory specifically and successfully predicts attitude change.\n(C) Dissonance creates active motivation to reduce the cognitive inconsistency.\n(D) Attitude change is the primary theoretical prediction, not just behavioral change."},
        {domainId:4, q:"The contact hypothesis (Allport) states that prejudice can be reduced when groups:", options:["Compete directly against each other for scarce resources in zero-sum intergroup rivalry contexts","Have equal status, pursue common goals, cooperate interdependently, and have institutional support","Simply exist in geographical proximity without any structured interaction or shared goals","Deliberately and systematically avoid all forms of intergroup contact and social interaction"], answer:1, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Correct: (B) Allport's conditions for prejudice reduction through contact: (1) equal status in the situation, (2) common goals, (3) cooperative interaction (not competitive), (4) support from authorities/institutions. Meta-analyses confirm these conditions optimize prejudice reduction.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) Competition can actually INCREASE prejudice (Sherif's Robbers Cave experiment).\n(C) Geographical proximity alone is insufficient — specific conditions are required.\n(D) Systematically avoiding contact maintains and reinforces existing stereotypes."},
        {domainId:4, q:"Self-serving bias refers to:", options:["Consistently acting selflessly in ways that exclusively benefit other people over oneself","Attributing successes to internal factors (ability) and failures to external factors (luck, difficulty)","Invariably blaming oneself for every negative outcome regardless of actual causal contribution","Accurately and objectively assessing one's causal role in both positive and negative outcomes"], answer:1, difficulty:"easy", rationale:"Correct: (B) Self-serving bias: success → 'I'm talented/worked hard' (internal). Failure → 'The test was unfair/bad luck' (external). Protects self-esteem. Cross-culturally variable — less pronounced in collectivist cultures. Related to actor-observer bias.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) It's self-serving, protecting self-esteem at the cost of accuracy.\n(C) The opposite — people systematically avoid self-blame.\n(D) It's a systematic cognitive bias away from objective accuracy."},
        {domainId:4, q:"Elaboration Likelihood Model (Petty & Cacioppo) describes two routes to persuasion:", options:["Both processing routes are fundamentally identical in their cognitive mechanisms and outcomes","Central route (deep argument processing) and peripheral route (relying on surface cues)","Only one single cognitive processing route to persuasion exists within the theoretical framework","Neither processing route involves any form of cognitive elaboration or information processing"], answer:1, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Correct: (B) Central route: high motivation and ability → careful scrutiny of argument quality → durable attitude change. Peripheral route: low motivation/ability → influenced by heuristics and cues (expert source, attractive speaker) → less durable change. Personal relevance increases central processing.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) The routes involve fundamentally different levels of cognitive processing.\n(C) Two distinct persuasion processing routes are specifically proposed.\n(D) Both routes involve cognitive processing but at qualitatively different levels."},
        {domainId:4, q:"Just-world hypothesis (Lerner) leads people to:", options:["Consistently help victims more because of heightened empathy for their unjust suffering","Blame victims for their misfortune to maintain the belief that the world is fundamentally fair","Actively and persistently seek true justice through institutional reform and social advocacy","Never attribute blame to anyone regardless of factual circumstances or behavioral contributions"], answer:1, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Correct: (B) Just-world belief: 'people get what they deserve.' When confronted with innocent suffering, this belief is threatened. People may victim-blame to restore the belief. Implications: blaming sexual assault victims, dismissing poverty as laziness, attributing illness to character.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) The just-world hypothesis often REDUCES helping through victim-blaming.\n(C) People maintain the illusion of justice through cognitive distortions, not reforms.\n(D) The bias specifically leads to attributing blame to innocent victims."},
        {domainId:4, q:"Collectivist cultures, compared to individualist cultures, tend to emphasize:", options:["Personal achievement and individual accomplishment above all other social and relational values","Group harmony, interdependence, loyalty to in-group, and fitting in rather than standing out","Only interpersonal competition and individual dominance over peers in social hierarchies","Individual rights, personal autonomy, and self-expression above all collective social obligations"], answer:1, difficulty:"easy", rationale:"Correct: (B) Collectivism: the self is defined in relation to others (interdependent self-construal). Values: group harmony, reciprocity, saving face, filial piety, duty. Common in East Asian, Latin American, African cultures. Affects motivation, attribution, communication, and conflict resolution.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) Personal achievement emphasis characterizes individualist cultures.\n(C) Individual competition characterizes individualist cultural values.\n(D) Individual rights emphasis defines individualist cultures specifically."},
        {domainId:4, q:"Groupthink (Janis) is most likely to occur when:", options:["Group members are maximally diverse in background and actively encourage open dissenting opinions","Groups are cohesive, insulated from outside information, have directive leadership, no systematic procedures","Group members consistently disagree openly and constructively challenge each other's reasoning","The phenomenon only occurs in small groups of fewer than five individuals and never larger ones"], answer:1, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Correct: (B) Groupthink antecedents: high cohesion, insulation, directive leadership, lack of norms for systematic evaluation, homogeneity of members, high stress with low hope for better solution. Symptoms: illusion of invulnerability, collective rationalization, self-censorship, mindguards.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) Diversity and dissent are precisely the conditions that PREVENT groupthink.\n(C) Open disagreement and constructive challenge prevent groupthink.\n(D) Groupthink can occur in decision-making groups of any size."},
        {domainId:4, q:"Implicit Association Test (IAT) measures:", options:["Only explicit consciously reported attitudes and beliefs through direct self-report questionnaires","Implicit automatic associations between concepts by measuring response time categorization differences","General cognitive intelligence as typically assessed by standardized psychometric IQ test batteries","Short-term and working memory capacity as assessed through digit span and serial recall tasks"], answer:1, difficulty:"easy", rationale:"Correct: (B) IAT (Greenwald): measures strength of implicit associations by comparing reaction times. Example: faster pairing of 'White' + 'Good' vs. 'Black' + 'Good' indicates an implicit pro-White bias. Controversial regarding predictive validity and malleability.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) The IAT specifically targets implicit (not explicit) unconscious associations.\n(C) Intelligence is measured by entirely different psychometric assessment instruments.\n(D) While reaction time is involved, the construct measured is associative, not memorial."},
        {domainId:4, q:"Deindividuation occurs when people:", options:["Become substantially more privately self-aware and personally accountable for their behavior","Feel anonymous in groups, leading to reduced self-awareness, lowered inhibitions, and uninhibited behavior","Invariably and always act prosocially and altruistically when immersed in large group settings","Only engage in the phenomenon when acting completely alone without any group social influence"], answer:1, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Correct: (B) Deindividuation (Zimbardo): anonymity + group immersion → reduced private self-awareness → weakened internal standards → uninhibited behavior (may be antisocial or prosocial). Factors: anonymity, diffusion of responsibility, arousing/distracting environments.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) Deindividuation specifically involves REDUCED private self-awareness.\n(C) Behavior can become antisocial or simply match whatever group norms exist.\n(D) It specifically occurs within group contexts that provide anonymity."},
        {domainId:4, q:"Intersectionality (Crenshaw) in psychology emphasizes:", options:["Only one single social identity dimension matters for understanding individual lived experiences","How multiple social identities (race, gender, class, sexuality) interact creating unique experiences","Individual social identities operate completely independently without influencing each other significantly","Only the experiences of majority group members are psychologically relevant for theoretical understanding"], answer:1, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Correct: (B) Intersectionality: social identities don't exist in isolation — they interact multiplicatively. A Black woman's experience isn't simply 'Black' + 'woman' but a unique intersection. Implications for assessment, treatment, research, and understanding systemic barriers.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) Multiple identities interact simultaneously and multiplicatively.\n(C) The core premise is that identities are fundamentally interconnected.\n(D) Intersectionality specifically examines experiences across all social positions."},
        {domainId:4, q:"Microaggressions are defined as:", options:["Major overt hate crimes involving direct physical violence against members of marginalized groups","Brief, commonplace slights communicating hostile or derogatory messages to marginalized groups, often unintentionally","Always consciously intentional and deliberately planned discriminatory behavioral actions against others","Phenomena occurring only in formal workplace settings and never in educational or social environments"], answer:1, difficulty:"easy", rationale:"Correct: (B) Microaggressions (Sue): subtle, often unintentional communications that convey negative messages to members of marginalized groups. Types: microassaults (deliberate), microinsults (rude/insensitive), microinvalidations (dismissing lived experiences). Cumulative impact on mental health.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) Microaggressions are specifically subtle, unlike overt hate crimes.\n(C) Many microaggressions are unintentional and outside conscious awareness.\n(D) They occur across all settings including schools, healthcare, and daily life."},

        // === Development (15) ===
        {domainId:2, q:"Ainsworth's Strange Situation identified attachment types including:", options:["Only one single universal attachment classification pattern observed across all studied infants","Secure, anxious-resistant/ambivalent, and anxious-avoidant (Main later added disorganized)","Only secure attachment patterns demonstrating consistent caregiver proximity-seeking reunion behavior","Only insecure attachment patterns characterized by avoidant or resistant caregiver reunion responses"], answer:1, difficulty:"easy", rationale:"Correct: (B) Strange Situation: structured observation of infant-caregiver separation/reunion. Secure (~60-65%): distressed but comforted. Anxious-resistant/ambivalent (~10%): extremely distressed, difficulty being comforted. Avoidant (~20%): appears indifferent. Disorganized (Main & Solomon): contradictory behaviors.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) Multiple distinct attachment classification patterns were identified.\n(C)(D) Both secure and insecure attachment types were systematically identified."},
        {domainId:2, q:"Bronfenbrenner's Ecological Systems Theory identifies nested levels including:", options:["Only the immediate microsystem of family and school without broader contextual influences","Microsystem, mesosystem, exosystem, macrosystem, and chronosystem — from immediate to broadest","Only a simple genes-versus-environment dichotomy without differentiated contextual system levels","Only school-based influences on child development without consideration of other ecological contexts"], answer:1, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Correct: (B) Bronfenbrenner: nested systems. Microsystem (immediate environments — family, school). Mesosystem (interactions between microsystems). Exosystem (indirect influences — parent's workplace). Macrosystem (culture, laws). Chronosystem (historical time/transitions).\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) Five distinct nested ecological systems are identified.\n(C) The model is far more complex than the nature-nurture dichotomy.\n(D) School is one microsystem among many influences on development."},
        {domainId:2, q:"Neural pruning during adolescence primarily involves:", options:["Growing entirely new brain regions that were not present during earlier childhood development","Elimination of unused synaptic connections, strengthening frequently used pathways ('use it or lose it')","No meaningful neurological brain changes occurring during the entire adolescent developmental period","Only myelination of existing neural axons without any corresponding synaptic connection elimination"], answer:1, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Correct: (B) Synaptic pruning: adolescent brain loses ~40% of synapses. Experience-dependent: frequently used connections strengthen (LTP), unused ones are eliminated. PFC is last to mature (mid-20s), explaining adolescent risk-taking, emotion regulation difficulties, and executive function development.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) Pruning removes unused connections rather than growing new brain regions.\n(C) Dramatic neurological brain changes occur throughout the adolescent period.\n(D) Both pruning and myelination occur, but the question specifically asks about pruning."},
        {domainId:2, q:"Successful aging theories include:", options:["Only decline-focused models emphasizing inevitable deterioration across all functional domains","Activity theory, disengagement theory, socioemotional selectivity theory, and SOC (Baltes)","Only biological aging processes without psychological or social adaptation considerations","Only cognitive decline trajectories without models of positive adaptation or compensatory strategies"], answer:1, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Correct: (B) Activity theory: staying active promotes well-being. Disengagement theory (Cumming & Henry): mutual withdrawal is natural (controversial). Socioemotional selectivity (Carstensen): as time horizon shrinks, emotional goals prioritized. SOC (Baltes): compensate for losses by selecting/optimizing remaining abilities.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) Modern theories emphasize positive adaptation, not just decline.\n(C) Successful aging is multidimensional — biological, psychological, and social.\n(D) Cognitive changes are one aspect; positive adaptation is also extensively studied."},
        {domainId:2, q:"Permissive parenting (Baumrind) is characterized by:", options:["High parental warmth combined with high behavioral control and consistent rule enforcement","High warmth/responsiveness but LOW demandingness/control — few rules and expectations set","Low parental warmth combined with high authoritarian behavioral control and strict rule enforcement","Low parental warmth combined with low behavioral control and general neglectful uninvolvement"], answer:1, difficulty:"easy", rationale:"Correct: (B) Permissive: warm and accepting but few rules, little discipline, child-directed. Outcomes: children may have poor self-regulation, lower academic achievement, but higher self-esteem and peer skills. Two subtypes: indulgent (warm) and neglectful/uninvolved.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) High warmth + high control describes authoritative parenting style.\n(C) Low warmth + high control describes authoritarian parenting style.\n(D) Low warmth + low control describes uninvolved/neglectful parenting."},
        {domainId:2, q:"Crystallized intelligence (Gc) tends to:", options:["Decline sharply and rapidly during young adulthood similar to fluid intelligence developmental trajectories","Remain stable or even increase throughout adulthood, reflecting accumulated knowledge and experience","Only be present during childhood developmental periods and completely absent during adult functioning","Equal fluid intelligence at all developmental ages showing identical growth and decline trajectories"], answer:1, difficulty:"easy", rationale:"Correct: (B) Gc: vocabulary, general knowledge, verbal comprehension — increases or stabilizes through adulthood. Based on education and cultural exposure. Contrasts with fluid intelligence (Gf), which peaks in late 20s and gradually declines. Cattell-Horn-Carroll theory.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) Sharp decline describes fluid intelligence developmental patterns, not crystallized.\n(C) Gc accumulates and persists throughout the entire lifespan.\n(D) Gc and Gf have distinctly different developmental trajectories."},
        {domainId:2, q:"Vygotsky's concept of private speech refers to:", options:["Talking secretively to others in whispered tones to exclude potential eavesdropping listeners","Children talking to themselves as a self-regulatory tool that eventually becomes internalized thought","A developmental language disorder requiring clinical speech-language pathology intervention services","A phenomenon occurring exclusively in adult populations and never observed in young children"], answer:1, difficulty:"easy", rationale:"Correct: (B) Private speech: self-directed speech that guides behavior and thinking. Ages 3-7: visible self-talk. Gradually internalizes to become inner speech (internal dialogue). Vygotsky viewed it as a crucial tool for cognitive development, unlike Piaget who saw it as egocentric.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) It's self-directed cognitive speech, not secretive interpersonal communication.\n(C) Private speech is a normal and adaptive developmental phenomenon.\n(D) It peaks in young childhood and internalizes; adults may use it under cognitive load."},
        {domainId:2, q:"Kübler-Ross's five stages of grief are:", options:["Only depression as the sole recognized stage within the entire grief process model","Denial, anger, bargaining, depression, and acceptance — though NOT necessarily sequential or universal","Only acceptance as the sole recognized stage within the entire grief process model","Only anger as the sole recognized emotional reaction within the entire grief process model"], answer:1, difficulty:"easy", rationale:"Correct: (B) DABDA model. Important caveats: stages are not linear, not universal, not prescriptive. Not everyone experiences all stages. Modern grief research emphasizes individual variability, continuing bonds, and dual-process model (Stroebe & Schut). Prolonged grief disorder now in DSM-5-TR.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A)(C)(D) All five distinct stages are part of the complete model, not just one."},
        {domainId:2, q:"Object permanence typically develops during:", options:["At the moment of birth with full cognitive understanding immediately present from day one","Piaget's sensorimotor stage, around 8-12 months of age through gradual cognitive development","During the adolescent formal operational stage of cognitive development around ages 11-15","Only during adulthood when metacognitive reflection abilities become fully neurologically mature"], answer:1, difficulty:"easy", rationale:"Correct: (B) Object permanence: understanding that objects continue to exist when out of sight. Develops in substage 4 of sensorimotor period (~8-12 months). Before this, 'out of sight, out of mind.' A-not-B error shows incomplete understanding. Baillargeon's research suggests earlier implicit understanding.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) Not present at birth — develops gradually over the first year.\n(C) Object permanence is established in infancy, not adolescence.\n(D) It's an early cognitive milestone achieved well before adulthood."},
        {domainId:2, q:"Preoperational thinking (Piaget, ages 2-7) is characterized by:", options:["Abstract logical thinking and systematic hypothesis testing about complex causal relationships","Egocentrism, centration, irreversibility, animism, and inability to perform conservation operations","Formal hypothesis testing through systematic manipulation of variables and deductive reasoning","Metacognitive awareness and sophisticated self-monitoring of one's own cognitive thinking processes"], answer:1, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Correct: (B) Preoperational limitations: egocentrism (can't take others' perspectives — three mountains task), centration (focus on one dimension), irreversibility (can't mentally reverse actions), animism (attributing life to objects), lack of conservation (changes in appearance = changes in quantity).\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) Abstract thinking characterizes the formal operational stage (11+).\n(C) Hypothesis testing characterizes the formal operational stage.\n(D) Metacognition develops significantly later in childhood/adolescence."},
        {domainId:2, q:"Adolescent egocentrism (Elkind) involves:", options:["Being fundamentally selfish and lacking any capacity for empathy toward other people's needs","The imaginary audience (believing others observe) and personal fable (believing one is unique/invulnerable)","Only clinical narcissistic personality disorder traits manifesting during the adolescent developmental period","A phenomenon exclusively observed in male adolescents and never demonstrated in female adolescents"], answer:1, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Correct: (B) Elkind's concepts: imaginary audience → heightened self-consciousness, performing for perceived observers. Personal fable → 'no one understands me,' belief in personal invulnerability ('it won't happen to me'). Both driven by developing but immature metacognitive abilities.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) It's a normal cognitive developmental phenomenon, not a character flaw.\n(C) Adolescent egocentrism is distinctly different from narcissistic personality traits.\n(D) Both males and females experience adolescent egocentrism equally."},
        {domainId:2, q:"Harlow's research with rhesus monkeys demonstrated:", options:["Only nutritional feeding needs matter for healthy infant attachment formation and development","The importance of contact comfort over feeding — infants preferred soft cloth over wire with food","Social isolation during infancy has no lasting effects on later social or emotional functioning","Only humans have attachment needs and other primate species do not form emotional caregiver bonds"], answer:1, difficulty:"easy", rationale:"Correct: (B) Harlow: infant monkeys overwhelmingly preferred the cloth-covered surrogate for comfort (contact comfort), going to the wire mother only briefly for food. Extended isolation produced severe social and emotional deficits. Demonstrated that attachment isn't based solely on feeding (contra drive-reduction theory).\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) Contact comfort was demonstrated to be more important than nutrition.\n(C) Isolation caused devastating and lasting social-emotional effects.\n(D) Attachment is clearly a cross-species phenomenon with evolutionary roots."},
        {domainId:2, q:"Theory of Mind (ToM) typically develops around:", options:["At the moment of birth with full understanding of others' mental states immediately present","Age 4-5, as demonstrated by passing false-belief tasks like the Sally-Anne test scenario","Around age 15 during the formal operational stage of adolescent cognitive development","Only in adulthood when prefrontal cortical executive functioning reaches complete neurological maturation"], answer:1, difficulty:"easy", rationale:"Correct: (B) ToM: understanding that others have different beliefs, desires, and knowledge than oneself. False-belief tasks: child must predict another's behavior based on the OTHER person's (false) belief, not reality. Most children pass by age 4-5. Delayed in autism spectrum disorder.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) Infants lack explicit ToM (though some implicit understanding exists earlier).\n(C) ToM develops in preschool years, not in adolescence.\n(D) ToM typically develops in early childhood, well before adulthood."},
        {domainId:2, q:"Gilligan's critique of Kohlberg centered on:", options:["The claim that Kohlberg was entirely wrong about all aspects of moral developmental theory","Kohlberg's model was biased toward JUSTICE orientation and underrepresented CARE orientation in reasoning","The assertion that morality doesn't actually develop over the human lifespan at all","The position that only men possess moral reasoning capacity and women are incapable of moral judgment"], answer:1, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Correct: (B) Gilligan: Kohlberg's stages were developed from an all-male sample and privileged abstract justice reasoning. Women may emphasize care, relationships, and responsibility. She proposed three levels of care: self-interest → self-sacrifice → balanced care. Note: subsequent research found smaller gender differences than Gilligan suggested.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) Gilligan didn't reject Kohlberg entirely but argued for a complementary perspective.\n(C) Both Gilligan and Kohlberg affirm that moral development occurs.\n(D) Both genders demonstrate moral reasoning capacity across developmental stages."},
        {domainId:2, q:"Scaffolding in Vygotsky's framework refers to:", options:["Building physical architectural structures and construction equipment used in building projects","Temporary support from a more knowledgeable other, gradually withdrawn as the learner gains competence","Permanent ongoing assistance that is never reduced regardless of the learner's developing abilities","Only formal classroom instruction occurring within traditional educational institutional school settings"], answer:1, difficulty:"easy", rationale:"Correct: (B) Scaffolding (Wood, Bruner, Ross — extending Vygotsky): adjustable support within the ZPD. As the child gains skill, the scaffold is faded. Examples: hints, prompts, modeling, breaking tasks into steps. Good teaching matches the scaffold to the learner's current level.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) Scaffolding is a metaphor for adjustable instructional and developmental support.\n(C) Scaffolding is explicitly TEMPORARY — it's progressively removed as competence grows.\n(D) Scaffolding occurs in any learning context including parenting, therapy, and coaching."},

        // === Research & Stats (10) ===
        {domainId:4, q:"External validity threats include:", options:["Only experimenter bias as investigated through double-blind controlled experimental research designs","Population validity (sample representativeness), ecological validity, and temporal validity (time periods)","Only measurement error affecting the reliability and consistency of dependent variable assessment","Only statistical power calculations determining the probability of correctly detecting true effects"], answer:1, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Correct: (B) External validity: can results generalize? Threats: population validity (WEIRD samples), ecological validity (lab vs. real world), temporal validity (historical period effects), Hawthorne effect (awareness of being studied), treatment variation (standardization across settings).\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) Experimenter bias threatens internal validity, not external.\n(C) Measurement error primarily threatens reliability and construct validity.\n(D) Statistical power affects Type II error probability, not generalizability."},
        {domainId:4, q:"A between-subjects design differs from a within-subjects design in that:", options:["They are fundamentally identical experimental designs producing exactly the same statistical outcomes","Different participants are in each condition (between), while SAME participants experience all (within)","Between-subjects designs always require random assignment while within-subjects never can use it","Within-subjects designs never employ counterbalancing procedures to control for order effects"], answer:1, difficulty:"easy", rationale:"Correct: (B) Between-subjects: each participant in only one condition (eliminates carryover effects but requires more participants). Within-subjects: each participant in all conditions (controls individual differences but has order/carryover effects requiring counterbalancing).\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) They are fundamentally different experimental design approaches.\n(C) Between-subjects can use random or non-random participant assignment.\n(D) Within-subjects designs typically USE counterbalancing specifically to address order effects."},
        {domainId:4, q:"Meta-analysis is a research method that:", options:["Only uses qualitative narrative data from ethnographic observational case study research","Quantitatively combines results across multiple studies using effect sizes to determine overall magnitude","Completely replaces the need for conducting any individual primary empirical research studies","Never employs any statistical techniques or quantitative analytical computational procedures"], answer:1, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Correct: (B) Meta-analysis: calculates a weighted average effect size across studies. Can examine moderators (why effects differ across studies). Advantages: increased power, precision, objectivity. Publication bias (file-drawer problem) is a key concern. Funnel plots and fail-safe N address this.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) Meta-analysis is quantitative and statistical by definition.\n(C) It builds upon individual studies rather than replacing them.\n(D) Advanced statistical techniques are absolutely central to meta-analysis."},
        {domainId:4, q:"Multiple regression analysis is used to:", options:["Only compare two groups using independent-samples t-test statistical inferential procedures","Predict a continuous criterion from two or more predictors, determining each predictor's unique contribution","Only describe data distributions using measures of central tendency and variability exclusively","Completely replace ANOVA for all statistical analyses involving multiple independent group comparisons"], answer:1, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Correct: (B) Multiple regression: Y = b₁X₁ + b₂X₂ + ... + bₙXₙ + a. Each b (beta weight) represents the unique contribution of that predictor, controlling for all others. R² = total variance explained. Hierarchical, stepwise, and simultaneous entry methods.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) Comparing two groups uses t-tests or ANOVA, not regression.\n(C) Regression is predictive/explanatory and not merely descriptive.\n(D) ANOVA and regression serve different (though mathematically related) analytical purposes."},
        {domainId:4, q:"Positive predictive value (PPV) of a test tells you:", options:["The test's overall psychometric reliability as measured by internal consistency or test-retest methods","The probability that someone who tests POSITIVE actually HAS the condition — influenced by base rate","The test's face validity as perceived by examinees taking the assessment instrument for screening","The total number of true negative classifications correctly identified by the diagnostic screening test"], answer:1, difficulty:"hard", rationale:"Correct: (B) PPV = true positives / (true positives + false positives). Critical insight: PPV depends heavily on base rate. A highly sensitive test will have LOW PPV when the condition is rare (lots of false positives relative to true positives). Clinically essential for interpretation.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) Reliability concerns measurement consistency, not predictive classification value.\n(C) Face validity is about subjective test appearance, not diagnostic accuracy.\n(D) True negatives relate specifically to negative predictive value (NPV)."},
        {domainId:4, q:"Cohen's d is an effect size measure that:", options:["Only measures statistical significance of null hypothesis tests through p-value calculations","Expresses the difference between two group means in standard deviation units (0.2=small, 0.5=medium, 0.8=large)","Completely replaces p-values entirely as the sole criterion for evaluating research findings","Only works with correlational research designs and cannot be applied to mean group differences"], answer:1, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Correct: (B) Cohen's d = (M₁ - M₂) / SDpooled. Standardized measure of the magnitude of a difference. Conventions (Cohen, 1988): 0.2 small, 0.5 medium, 0.8 large. Important because statistical significance doesn't tell you the SIZE of the effect.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) Cohen's d measures effect magnitude, not statistical significance.\n(C) Effect sizes complement p-values rather than entirely replacing them.\n(D) Cohen's d is specifically for mean differences; r or η² are for correlations/ANOVA."},
        {domainId:4, q:"A factorial design is defined as:", options:["Having only one single independent variable with multiple levels but no interaction possibilities","A design with TWO or more independent variables (factors), allowing examination of main effects and interactions","Having no control group or comparison condition within the entire experimental research design","Only using qualitative narrative data collection methods without any quantitative measurement procedures"], answer:1, difficulty:"easy", rationale:"Correct: (B) Factorial: ≥2 IVs studied simultaneously. A 2 × 3 design has two factors (one with 2 levels, one with 3). Main effects: overall effect of each factor. Interaction: the effect of one factor depends on the level of another. Efficient and ecologically valid.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) One IV describes a simple experimental design, not a factorial design.\n(C) Factorial designs typically include control conditions within their structure.\n(D) Factorial designs are quantitative experimental research designs."},
        {domainId:4, q:"In a positive skew distribution:", options:["The mean exactly equals the median and mode in a perfectly symmetrical normal distribution","The tail extends RIGHT, with Mean > Median > Mode — most scores cluster at the lower end","The tail extends to the left with most scores concentrated at the upper higher end","There is no identifiable tail in any direction and scores are uniformly evenly distributed"], answer:1, difficulty:"easy", rationale:"Correct: (B) Positive skew: right tail. Floor effect — most scores are low with few high outliers. The mean is pulled toward the tail. Examples: income distribution, response times. In negative skew: tail left, Mode > Median > Mean (ceiling effect).\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) Mean = median = mode only in a perfectly normal symmetrical distribution.\n(C) Left tail describes a negatively skewed distribution, not positive.\n(D) All distributions have identifiable tails with varying distributional shapes."},
        {domainId:4, q:"MANOVA differs from ANOVA because:", options:["They are completely identical statistical procedures producing exactly the same analytical results","MANOVA has multiple DEPENDENT variables, examining group differences across several outcomes simultaneously","MANOVA simply has more independent variables than standard ANOVA without changing dependent variables","MANOVA doesn't use any F-test statistics or related inferential testing computational procedures"], answer:1, difficulty:"hard", rationale:"Correct: (B) MANOVA: multiple DVs analyzed together. Advantages: controls Type I error inflation (vs. running multiple ANOVAs), accounts for DV correlations, can detect multivariate patterns. Uses Wilks' lambda, Pillai's trace, Hotelling's trace, or Roy's largest root as test statistics.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) They differ fundamentally in the number of dependent variables analyzed.\n(C) More IVs describes factorial ANOVA, not the defining feature of MANOVA.\n(D) MANOVA uses F-approximations for its multivariate test statistics."},
        {domainId:4, q:"Regression to the mean refers to:", options:["Genuinely improving over time due to effective treatment intervention or developmental maturation","The statistical tendency for extreme scores to move TOWARD the average on subsequent measurements","Getting progressively worse over time due to deterioration or declining functional abilities","A type of systematic cognitive bias affecting human judgment and probabilistic decision making"], answer:1, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Correct: (B) Regression to the mean (Galton): extreme scores contain more measurement error → on retest, they're likely to be less extreme. Threats internal validity: an extremely low-performing group may show 'improvement' simply due to regression, not treatment effectiveness.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) It's a statistical artifact, not evidence of genuine improvement.\n(C) Extreme scores in either direction move toward the mean on retesting.\n(D) It's a statistical measurement phenomenon, not a cognitive judgment bias."}
    ];

    batch50.forEach(q => {
        const domain = EPPPData.domains.find(d => d.id === q.domainId);
        if (domain) {
            domain.questions.push({
                q: q.q, options: q.options, answer: q.answer,
                difficulty: q.difficulty, rationale: q.rationale,
                domainId: q.domainId, domainName: domain.name
            });
        }
    });

    console.log(`PasstheEPPP: Loaded ${batch50.length} additional questions (batch 50).`);
})();
